  "prompt": "Is Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa an avatar?",
  "response": "Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa is regarded by many of his followers and admirers as an avatar, which in Hinduism typically refers to a divine incarnation or appearance of a deity on Earth. Ramakrishna, who lived in the 19th century in Bengal, India, is considered a mystic and saint, known for his deep spiritual experiences and devotion to the goddess Kali, as well as for his teachings that emphasized the universality of all religions.\n\nHowever, the classification of Sri Ramakrishna as an avatar is ultimately a matter of personal belief and spiritual interpretation. Different devotees and spiritual organizations may view him in various lights, ranging from a great spiritual teacher to an incarnation of the divine. The Ramakrishna Movement, which includes the Ramakrishna Mission and Math founded by his disciple Swami Vivekananda, often regards him as an avatar or divine personality, emphasizing his role as a unifier of different religious paths.",
